div.p:
But come we on to a second vse of exhortation 
                           Vse 2 to vs all, as euer wee desire to be assured that wee are true Israelites, the Israel of God, within the speciall Couenant of grace, labour what you can to attaine this one heart here promised. Many motiues wee might vse to perswade you hereunto. There is but one God, one Christ, one Spirit, one truth one Gospell, one heauen: besides, thou art but one man, and one heart is enough for one man, get it therefore: It is comfortable:

 for it is an euidence of our vprightnesse: And it is profitable, for it vnites a man to himselfe in all God Seruices, it deliuers him from many temptations, from many distractions, &c. Gods people vsually complaine of nothing more then this, that in the doing of holy duties, their hearts are diuided, their thoughts scattered vp & down, and will not be confined to the place where they sit; besides, they finde a flatnesse and deadnesse of spirit in all. Now a present remedy against all distraction and disturbance in this kinde, is this onenesse, we here presse you vnto; for when a Christian hath gathered all his forces into one, this addes feruour to his prayers, and puts life and spirit into all his other seruices. If therefore you would haue your hearts at command in holy duties. If you would be assured of your vprightnes, if lastly, you would please God, who hates all doubling and diuision, doe all you can to get one heart, which that you may;

1. All vnrigteous persons. 1 Cor. 6.9, 10. Know yee not that the vnrighteous shall not inherite the Kingdome of God? Neither fornicators, nor idolaters, &c; 'tis expresse Scripture. Not, but that such may be saued, if they repent: for such were some of you, but ye are washed, &c: ver. 11. but if they continue to be children of disobedience, such as will not be perswaded, the word (
                        〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
                     ) signifies, then there's no heauen to be had. 2. All vnmercifull men, for to such it shall be said, Depart from me; I haue nothing to say to you, Matth. 25. for I was an hungered, and yee gaue mee no meate, &c. Thirdly, all vnholy men: for without holinesse none can see God, God will see such a one to his terror; but he shall neuer see God to his comfort. So Ioh. 3.3, 5. Except a man be borne anew, he cannot see the Kingdome of God. And Heb. 12.14.

Yea, if it were true and right; 
                           Obiect. 
                         but how shall I know that?

I answer; 
                        Answ. 
                      There is an act of the vnderstanding, which is to take notice, and be sensible if a wrong done me. 2. there is an act of the memory, which recoyles vpon it selfe, and remembers that such a thing was done. 3. there is an act of the will, an auersenesse and distasting of the iniury, whereby I am offended and displeased thereat. These three acts no man can haue the command of in himselfe, or hinder; but that when he is wronged hee shall see it, remember such a thing to haue beene done, and be moued with iust dislike of it. But then yet there must be 1. an act of the Iudgement, whereby, though there haue beene a trespasse done me, yet vpon confession and satisfaction, I will not impute it, or reckon it to him that hath done it: though it sticke in the booke, yet it shall be crossed out, as it were. And 2. for matter of Reuenge, I must alwayes forgiue, as euer I looke to be forgiuen of God, not returning like for like; not rendring reproach for reproach, or one iniury for another, but contrarily blessing those that curse me, and ouercomming euill with good: for herein Religion and Christianity triumphs ouer all Morality.

Fourthly, for the affects and fruites of this spirituall mercy: It is actiue, first inwardly, secondly outwardly. Inwardly, it sets all the powers of the soule • a worke, for the reliefe of the party distressed. And 1. for the mind and vnderstanding of a man, mercy makes him: 1. consider his case, as the mercifull man is discribed to do, Psal. 41.1. it bends his vnderstanding to the party affected, afflicted, makes his thoughts dwell vpon that subiect, vpon his debts, vpon his misery, pouerty, &c. it feeds his thoughts with the consideration of the others miserable estate, makes him thinke, he's a man as well as I, &c. 2. It causeth him to cast about, and deuise how to relieue and succour him, according to that expression of Salomon, Prou. 14.22. Mercy and truth, saith he, shall be to them that deuise good. It makes a man bethinke himselfe which way he may goe to worke, to relieue and helpe such as are poore, sicke, or in
any other affliction, it sharpens his wits, and sets him a proiecting, according to that wee read, Esay. 32.8. The liberall man deuiseth liberall things; he studies on his bed, and casts about how he may best doe to releue such as are in need of him. And this now is mercies first worke vpon the vnderstanding, it makes a man to consider the needy and afflicted, and to cast about by what meanes best to relieue them, you may see it in euery mother toward her sicke child, shee cannot forget it, whatsoeuer she is about, but studies still whither to goe, what meanes to vse, what course to take to ease the poore chid. But secondly, as mercy works vpon the mind, so also vpon the memory of a man, which now presents vnto him the misery of his neighbour, wheresoeuer he goes, he heares him groaning, he sees him sweating, tossing, panting, he cannot possibly forget him whereuer he is, whateuer he does. It makes a man search and rifle into the bottome of his memory (that chest of the soule) to bethinke himselfe, and call to mind what haue I read that might doe this poore man good? what haue I heard? what haue I tryed and found by experience, that might yeeld him ease, do him comfort? Thirdly, as it works vpon the memory, so likewsie vpon the will, it makes a man both nolle malum, as to be sorry fo his sicknesse, paine, distresse, and velle bonum, to doe him all the good that may be done, he longs for the good of his distressed neighbour, desires it earnestly, prayes heartily for it, and vseth all good meanes to effect it. And this that inward act of mercy;
which it hath vpon the vnderstanding, memory and will of him, in whom it is transforming him after a sort into the person afflicted, making him feele the sorrowes, sigh in the sufferings, bleed in the wounds of his neighbour, liue in him, dye with him, &c.
